prompt: Denise Ohio restores a bit of the word’s luster with this surprisingly compelling portrait of Frank Minden. Who? An ordinary, hard-working man, a WWII vet and master diesel machinist, the 76-year-old Minden has never
natural_text: signed a multimillion-dollar contract with a sports franchise or refused an Oscar in honor of the worthy cause of the day. But in the short space of thirty minutes, Ohio illustrates what makes this St. Louis man so admired and respected by those around him. Interviews with Minden’s wife and seven adult children reveal the kind of family anecdotes and obviously oft-told tales that shouldn’t be of interest to anyone not Minden, but the sincere adoration of his family lends a potency to them, perhaps by reminding us of our own familial bonds… or highlighting a lack thereof. Reticent and staid, Minden doesn’t have much to say for himself, but Ohio’s artfully simple footage of him at work in his shop says more about the stolid nobility of this ordinary man than words ever could. Shot partially in digital form and edited digitally, Family Business is a lovingly produced family album, a high-tech movie about a decidedly low-tech hero… yes, hero.
unwatermarked_sample:
been a fixture in the small town for decades.
Denise, inspired by his story, decided to take a series of photos of Frank in his natural environment, at his beloved workbench. There’s a quiet dignity to the images, which are augmented with Minden’s own words, and the story of his life and career. The book is a labor of love, but Denise’s passion for her subject comes through.
The book was awarded an honorable mention in the 2014 International Book Awards in the category of Biography.
